SIMPLE: load
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Load
<hw>Load</hw> <pr>(l⟦omac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>lode</ets> load, way; properly the same word as <ets>lode</ets>,
but confused with <ets>lade</ets>, <ets>load</ets>, v. See
<er>Lade</er>, <er>Lead</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, <er>Lode</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A burden; that which is laid on or put in anything for
conveyance; that which is borne or sustained; a weight; <as>as, a heavy
<ex>load</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He might such a <qex>load</qex>⟦br⟧
To town with his ass carry.</q> <rj><qau>Gower.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The quantity which can be carried or drawn in some
specified way; the contents of a cart, barrow, or vessel; that which
will constitute a cargo; lading.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which burdens, oppresses, or grieves the mind
or spirits; <as>as, a <ex>load</ex> of care</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ A . . .
<xex>load</xex> of guilt.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Ray.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧ Our life's a
<xex>load</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A particular measure for certain articles, being as
much as may be carried at one time by the conveyance commonly used for
the article measured; <as>as, a <ex>load</ex> of wood; a <ex>load</ex>
of hay</as>; specifically, five quarters.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The charge of a firearm; <as>as, a <ex>load</ex> of
powder</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Weight or violence of blows.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>The work done by a steam engine
or other prime mover when working.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>The amount of work that a person, group, or machine
is assigned to perform; <as>as, the boss distributed the <ex>load</ex>
evenly among his employees</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>The device or devices that
consume power from a power supply.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Engineering)</fld> <def>The weight or force that a
structural support bears or is designed to bear; the object that creates
that force.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Load line</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Load water
line</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the line on the outside of
a vessel indicating the depth to which it sinks in the water when
loaded.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Burden; lading; weight; cargo. See
<er>Burden</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Load</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Load
<hw>Load</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Loaded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Loading</conjf>. <xex>Loaden</xex> is obsolete, and
<xex>laden</xex> belongs to <xex>lade</xex>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To lay a load or burden on or in, as on a horse or in a cart; to
charge with a load, as a gun; to furnish with a lading or cargo, as a
ship; hence, to add weight to, so as to oppress or embarrass; to heap
upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I strive all in vain to <qex>load</qex> the cart.</q>
<rj><qau>Gascoigne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <qex>loaden</qex> me with many spoils.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those honors deep and broad, wherewith⟦br⟧
Your majesty <qex>loads</qex> our house.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 863 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To adulterate or drug; <as>as, to <ex>load</ex>
wine</as>.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To magnetize.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Loaded dice</b></col>, <cd>dice with one side made
heavier than the others, so that the number on the opposite side will
come up oftenest.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>load-bearing</ent>⟦br⟧
